@startuml C4_Pattern_ResourceAllocation
!include https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plantuml-stdlib/C4-PlantUML/master/C4_Component.puml

title YAWL Workflow Pattern - Resource-Based Task Assignment

Boundary(task, "Task") {
    Component(resource_task, "ResourceTask", "Task", "Assign to resource pool")
    Component(requirements, "TaskRequirements", "Spec", "Required skills")
}

Boundary(resource_pool, "Resource Pool") {
    Component(participants, "Participants", "People", "Available people")
    Component(participant_skills, "ParticipantSkills", "Capabilities", "Who can do what")
    Component(participant_capacity, "ParticipantCapacity", "Limits", "Max tasks")
}

Boundary(allocation_engine, "Allocation Engine") {
    Component(skill_matcher, "SkillMatcher", "Logic", "Match skills to task")
    Component(load_balancer, "LoadBalancer", "Logic", "Distribute evenly")
    Component(capacity_checker, "CapacityChecker", "Logic", "Check availability")
    Component(cost_optimizer, "CostOptimizer", "Logic", "Minimize cost")
}

Boundary(assignment, "Assignment") {
    Component(assignment_strategy, "AssignmentStrategy", "Choose", "Specific person or pool")
    Component(notification, "Notification", "Alert", "Notify assignee")
    Component(worklist, "Worklist", "Queue", "Task appears in queue")
}

task --> requirements: Specifies
requirements --> skill_matcher: Matches against
participants --> participant_skills: Have
participant_skills --> skill_matcher: Filtered by
participant_capacity --> capacity_checker: Checked by
skill_matcher --> load_balancer: Ranks candidates
load_balancer --> cost_optimizer: Optimizes
cost_optimizer --> assignment_strategy: Chooses
assignment_strategy --> notification: Notifies
notification --> worklist: Queues

Note as N1
Resource-Based Assignment Pattern:

Task Requirements:
- Required skills (Java, Spring, Microservices)
- Minimum experience level (Senior)
- Preferred location (same timezone)
- Estimated duration (4-8 hours)
- Priority (normal/high/critical)

Resource Pool:
- Participants (people, roles, systems)
- Skills: Java, Spring, Microservices, etc.
- Certifications: AWS Solutions Architect
- Availability: Free/busy calendar
- Capacity: Max concurrent tasks

Allocation Algorithm:

1. Filter by Required Skills
   - Must have all required skills
   - Consider certification level

2. Check Capacity
   - Max tasks: <5 concurrent
   - Check calendar availability
   - Consider workload trend

3. Calculate Score
   - Skill match: 80 points max
   - Experience level: 10 points max
   - Availability: 10 points max
   - Score = skill + experience + availability

4. Rank Candidates
   - Sort by score (descending)
   - Break ties by load (least busy first)
   - Consider cost optimization

5. Assign
   - Assign to top-ranked candidate
   - If unavailable: fallback to next
   - If none available: escalate to manager

Assignment Strategies:

Direct Assignment:
- Assign to specific person (best fit)
- Example: Senior architect for design

Pool Assignment:
- Assign to role (anyone with role)
- Example: "Any customer service rep"

Round-Robin:
- Distribute evenly across candidates
- Track assignment count
- Fair distribution

Load-Balanced:
- Assign to least-busy candidate
- Minimize max load
- Improve throughput

Cost-Optimized:
- Assign to lowest-cost candidate
- Consider skill level premium
- Balance cost vs quality

Escalation Rules:

If No Match:
- Escalate to manager
- Manager manually assigns
- Or wait for participant

If Multiple Equal:
- Consider availability
- Consider timezone
- Consider team balance

Constraints:
- Never exceed max capacity
- Respect skill requirements
- Honor availability windows
- Maintain SLA (assign <5 min)

Notifications:
- Email: Task assignment
- Calendar: Block time
- Worklist UI: Appear in task list
- Slack: Optional reminder
End note

SHOW_LEGEND()
@enduml
